# Forehand Angle Reference

Coaching heuristics for bucketing tracked forehand swings by shot intent.
Two angles matter most:

- **Racket face angle** — how closed the strings are relative to vertical at contact.
- **Swing path angle** — how steeply the racket travels low-to-high through contact.

These should be validated against your own captured data once `features.py`
is computing them — treat the ranges below as starting thresholds, not fixed constants.

---

## 1. Flat Drive

| Metric | Target range |
|---|---|
| Racket face angle | ~10–20° closed |
| Swing path angle | ~10–20° upward |

- Lowest topspin, highest raw pace.
- Smallest margin over the net — less forgiving of timing errors.
- Contact point tends to be slightly further out in front of the body.

---

## 2. Standard Topspin

| Metric | Target range |
|---|---|
| Racket face angle | ~30–45° closed |
| Swing path angle | ~20–35° upward |

- The default rally shot for most players — balances pace, spin, and margin.
- Racket head dips below ball height before the low-to-high swing through contact.

---

## 3. Heavy Topspin / Loop

| Metric | Target range |
|---|---|
| Racket face angle | ~45°+ closed |
| Swing path angle | ~35–50° upward |

- Trades pace for margin and a higher, deeper bounce.
- Common on high defensive balls or when working a player out of position.
- Steepest low-to-high path of the three; face angle needs to close further to keep the ball in.

---

## Notes for `features.py`

When bucketing a tracked swing into one of the three categories:
1. Compute swing path angle from wrist/racket position ~3 frames pre-contact to the contact frame.
2. Compute racket face angle from racket-head orientation relative to the ball's incoming trajectory at the contact frame.
3. Classify using the ranges above, but log the raw angle values too — thresholds may need tuning once you see real distributions from your footage.